---CONTEXT_START---

Project Context
Overview
An autonomous obstacle-avoiding RC car powered by radar and ultrasonic sensors. A beginner-friendly IoT project that transforms a standard ~15cm RC car into a self-driving indoor robot using an ESP32 microcontroller.

Background
User: Beginner to electronics/programming
Platform: Existing RC car (~15cm) repurposed with new electronics
Environment: Indoor use only (home/office floors)
Budget: ~$80 USD
Success Criteria
Car drives autonomously without human input
Successfully detects and avoids obstacles (walls, furniture, objects)
Operates continuously for 15+ minutes per charge
Beginner can assemble and understand the code
Constraints
Limited to ~$80 budget
Indoor operation only
Must fit on small ~15cm RC car chassis
Beginner-friendly components and code
No advanced navigation (no mapping, no destination targeting)
---CONTEXT_END---

---MVP_START---

Minimum Viable Product (MVP)
Core Features
Feature	Description	Justification
Forward obstacle detection	LD2410C radar detects objects 0.5-4m ahead	Primary collision avoidance - radar works in all lighting conditions
Side awareness	HC-SR04 ultrasonics on left/right	Enables intelligent turning decisions
Autonomous steering	Turn toward clearer side when obstacle detected	Core autonomous behavior
Motor control	Forward, stop, left turn, right turn	Basic movement requirements
Speed control	PWM-based speed adjustment	Smoother operation, safer indoors
Out of Scope (Future Enhancements)
Room mapping / SLAM
Destination navigation
Mobile app control
Voice commands
Outdoor operation
Reverse driving (keeps logic simple for MVP)
Success Metrics
Avoids 90%+ of obstacles in a cluttered room
Zero collisions at slow/medium speed
Runs 15+ minutes continuously
Assembly completed in one weekend
Tech Stack
Microcontroller: ESP32 DevKit V1
Primary Sensor: LD2410C 24GHz mmWave radar
Secondary Sensors: HC-SR04 ultrasonic x2
Motor Control: L298N dual H-bridge driver
Power: Existing RC car battery or 2S LiPo (7.4V)
Language: Arduino C++ (beginner-friendly)
IDE: Arduino IDE or PlatformIO
---MVP_END---

---PRD_START---

Product Requirements Document (PRD)
Vision
Create "RadarRover" - a beginner's first autonomous robot that demonstrates real-world IoT sensor fusion, teaching foundational concepts in electronics, programming, and robotics through a fun, tangible project.

Hardware Requirements
Components List
Component	Model	Quantity	Purpose	Est. Cost
Microcontroller	ESP32 DevKit V1	1	Main processor	$8
Radar Sensor	LD2410C	1	Front obstacle detection	$6
Ultrasonic Sensor	HC-SR04	2	Left/right side detection	$4
Motor Driver	L298N	1	DC motor control	$4
Battery	2S LiPo 7.4V 1500mAh (or reuse existing)	1	Power supply	$15
Voltage Regulator	LM7805 or buck converter	1	5V for ESP32/sensors	$2
Wiring	Jumper wires, connectors	1 set	Connections	$3
Mounting	Screws, zip ties, double-sided tape	1 set	Physical assembly	$3
TOTAL				~$45
~$35 buffer remaining for upgrades or mistakes

Wiring Overview
Battery (7.4V)
    ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ L298N (motor power)
    ‚îÇ     ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ DC Motors (left/right)
    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Buck Converter ‚Üí 5V
          ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ ESP32
          ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ LD2410C
          ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ HC-SR04 x2
Pin Mapping (ESP32)
Pin	Connection
GPIO16, 17	L298N IN1, IN2 (left motor)
GPIO18, 19	L298N IN3, IN4 (right motor)
GPIO21, 22	L298N ENA, ENB (PWM speed)
GPIO4 (RX2)	LD2410C TX
GPIO5	HC-SR04 Left (Trig+Echo shared)
GPIO23	HC-SR04 Right (Trig+Echo shared)
Software Requirements
Core Logic (Pseudocode)
loop:
    front_distance = read_radar()
    left_distance = read_ultrasonic(LEFT)
    right_distance = read_ultrasonic(RIGHT)
    
    if front_distance > SAFE_THRESHOLD:
        drive_forward()
    else:
        stop()
        if left_distance > right_distance:
            turn_left(500ms)
        else:
            turn_right(500ms)
Configurable Parameters
SAFE_THRESHOLD
- distance to trigger avoidance (default: 40cm)
TURN_DURATION
- how long to turn (default: 500ms)
BASE_SPEED
- PWM motor speed (default: 150/255)
Libraries Required
ld2410
- radar communication
NewPing
- ultrasonic sensors
Built-in ESP32 PWM functions
Non-Functional Requirements
Requirement	Target
Response time	<200ms from detection to steering
Power consumption	15+ min runtime
Reliability	Operates without crashes/reboots
Maintainability	Clean, commented code
Modularity	Easy to add sensors later
User Stories
As a beginner, I want clear wiring diagrams so I don't fry components
As a user, I want the car to drive itself when powered on (no setup)
As a user, I want it to smoothly avoid walls and furniture
As a learner, I want readable code with comments explaining each section
As a tinkerer, I want to easily adjust sensitivity and speed
